'''Definition'''

Abandoned child syndrome is the behavioral or psychological condition that a child develops as a result of one or both parents disappearing from their lives. Many countries, like Russia and China, have an alarmingly high rate of abandoned children. In a report done by Human Rights comities there were more than 100,000 children per year abandon in Russia. Parents leave their children for many reasons. Some include being in trouble with the law, financially insecure, the child is mentally or physically challenged, and sometimes countries that have population control policies. Parents who leave their children with reasons or without, cause irreversible problems. [1]It is psychologically harmful to children to be deprived of a healthy relationship with one parent. There is substantial research that indicates that children need contact with adults of both sexes for balanced development.[5] 


'''Symptoms'''

'''Alienation from the environment'''-withdrawn from social activities, resistant towards others [7]

'''Guilt'''- an effective state in which one experiences conflict at having done something one believes shuold not have done (often associated with depression) [8]

'''Fear and uncertainty''' - clingy behaviors, insecurities [2]

'''Sleep and eating disorders''' - Suffer from inadequate food [2]

'''Physical ailments''' - fatigue, depression, lack of energy 
and creativity, anger, grieving. [2]


'''Recovery'''

To relieve the stress of such a shocking event children should be creative and play.  Playing is a non-threatening way for children to work through stressful and traumatic situations.  Creative play gives children an outlet to make something "better" and helps them overcome feelings of powerlessness. [3]

'''Other'''

The Abandoned Child Syndrome is not listed in the Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders (fourth edition). [4]



